SIMPLE: dibasic
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dibasic
<hw>Di*ba"sic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>di-</ets> + <ets>basic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Having
two acid hydrogen atoms capable of replacement by basic atoms or
radicals, in forming salts; bibasic; -- said of acids, as oxalic or
sulphuric acids. Cf. <er>Diacid</er>, <er>Bibasic</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the case of certain acids <xex>dibasic</xex> and
<xex>divalent</xex> are not synonymous; as, tartaric acid is
<xex>tetravalent</xex> and <xex>dibasic</xex>, lactic acid is
<xex>divalent</xex> but <xex>monobasic</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dibasicity</ent>⟦br⟧
